{
  "doc_id": "22901",
  "text": "In typical neutron diffraction measurements of residual stress on a white beam source, the detector view is focused using radial collimators [CITATION_1] [14] [15] [16] defining the gauge volume in the third dimension. This practice both provides depth resolution as well as ensures that the gauge volume does not move with respect to the diffractometer during profiling resulting in large fictitious strain observations [17] . However, due to the thin foil nature of these samples, that practice was not possible (while retaining reasonable count times) and diffraction data was collected from the entire thickness of the samples.",
  "correct_citation": {
